{"parse":{"title":"Moments (poem)","pageid":30404798,"revid":859494829,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Moments</b> (<a href=\"/wiki/Spanish_language\" title=\"Spanish language\">Spanish</a>: <i><span lang=\"es\">Instantes</span></i>) is the title of a text wrongly attributed to <a href=\"/wiki/Argentine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Argentine\">Argentine</a> writer <a href=\"/wiki/Jorge_Luis_Borges\" title=\"Jorge Luis Borges\">Jorge Luis Borges</a>. It was widely spread through articles, compilations, posters and <a href=\"/wiki/Email\" title=\"Email\">email</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Chain_letters\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Chain letters\">chain letters</a>, mainly in Spanish.\n</p><p>Spanish versions, with some variations, consist of a first person narrated poem about an 85-year-old person who regrets not having enjoyed some simple pleasures during his life and instead having focused on safety and correctness. \n</p><p>The vocabulary, syntax and style do not match those of Borges.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Original_text_and_author\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Original text and author</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#English_and_Spanish_apocryphal_versions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">English and Spanish apocryphal versions</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Most_important_wrong_attributions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Most important wrong attributions</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Original_text_and_author\">Original text and author</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Moments_(poem)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Original text and author\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The first known version of the text was authored by American humorist and cartoonist <a href=\"/wiki/Don_Herold\" title=\"Don Herold\">Don Herold</a>, and published by <a href=\"/wiki/College_Humor_(magazine)\" title=\"College Humor (magazine)\">College Humor</a> before 1935, or perhaps early that year, under the title \"I'd Pick More Daisies\". <sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Herold's text is in prose, and it lacks the melancholic tone of the Spanish poem. E.g.:\n</p>\n<blockquote><p>If I had my life to live over, I'd try to make more mistakes next time. I would relax. I would limber up. I would be sillier than I have been this trip. I know of very few things that I would take seriously. I would be crazier. I would be less hygienic. I would take more chances. I would take more trips. I would climb more mountains and swim more rivers. I would burn up more gasoline. I would eat more ice cream and less bran.</p></blockquote>\n<p>Herold published a revised version in the October 1953 number of <a href=\"/wiki/Reader%27s_Digest\" title=\"Reader&#39;s Digest\">Reader's Digest</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-borges.pitt.edu_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-borges.pitt.edu-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"English_and_Spanish_apocryphal_versions\">English and Spanish apocryphal versions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Moments_(poem)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: English and Spanish apocryphal versions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Another English version, attributed to one Nadine Stair or Nadine Strain, starts:<sup id=\"cite_ref-borges.pitt.edu_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-borges.pitt.edu-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<blockquote><p>If I Had My Life to Live Over I'd dare to make more mistakes next time. I'd relax, I would limber up. I would be sillier than I have been this trip. I would take fewer things seriously. I would take more chances. I would climb more mountains and swim more rivers. I would eat more ice cream and less beans.</p></blockquote><p>This version, supposedly written by Nadine Stair, is the most common version in North America. However it is unlikely that Nadine Stair ever existed. Just how Nadine Stair came to attributed as the author is unknown. Nonetheless, what is known is that Sandar Martz produced an anthology of poems dealing with women and aging <sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>. In this anthology she attributes Don Herold's poem with some modifications to a certain Nadine Stair. This was likely done because the anthology was written by women for women, and it would not have appealed to the readers to have a poem written by a man in the anthology.      \n</p><p>One of the most spread Spanish versions wrongly attributed to Borges starts with the following verses:\n</p>\n<table>\n\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>\n<dl><dd><b>Spanish apocryphal text</b><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>\n</td>\n<td>\n<dl><dd><b>English translation</b></dd></dl>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<dl><dd><i>Si pudiera vivir nuevamente mi vida</i></dd>\n<dd><i>En la pr\u00f3xima tratar\u00eda de cometer m\u00e1s errores</i></dd>\n<dd><i>No intentar\u00eda ser tan perfecto, me relajar\u00eda m\u00e1s</i></dd>\n<dd><i>Ser\u00eda m\u00e1s tonto de lo que he sido, de hecho</i></dd>\n<dd><i>tomar\u00eda muy pocas cosas con seriedad</i></dd>\n<dd><i>Ser\u00eda menos higi\u00e9nico</i></dd></dl>\n</td>\n<td>\n<dl><dd><i>If I could live my life again</i></dd>\n<dd><i>Next time I would try to make more mistakes</i></dd>\n<dd><i>I would not try to be so perfect, I would relax more</i></dd>\n<dd><i>I would be sillier than I was, in fact</i></dd>\n<dd><i>I would take very few things seriously</i></dd>\n<dd><i>I would be less hygienic</i></dd></dl>\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Most_important_wrong_attributions\">Most important wrong attributions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Moments_(poem)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Most important wrong attributions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Spanish versions with the shape of a poem were wrongly attributed to Borges by literary magazines like Mexican <i>Plural</i> (May 1989, pages 4\u20135)<sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated1_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated1-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> and books (such as <a href=\"/wiki/Elena_Poniatowska\" title=\"Elena Poniatowska\">Elena Poniatowska</a>'s \"Todo M\u00e9xico\", page 144).<sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated1_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated1-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On December 2005, Irish pop singer <a href=\"/wiki/Bono\" title=\"Bono\">Bono</a>, read in Spanish some of the lines of the poem on Mexican TV show <a href=\"/wiki/Telet%C3%B3n_(Mexico)\" title=\"Telet\u00f3n (Mexico)\">Telet\u00f3n M\u00e9xico 2005</a> and attributed them to the \"Chilean poet Borges.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The attribution error was so extended that even the poet and scholar <a href=\"/wiki/Alastair_Reid\" title=\"Alastair Reid\">Alastair Reid</a> translated one of the Spanish versions into English under the belief that it was a work from Borges. Reid's translations starts,\n</p>\n<blockquote>\n<dl><dd>If I were able to live my life again,</dd>\n<dd>next time I would try to make more mistakes.</dd>\n<dd>I would not try to be so perfect. I would be more relaxed.</dd>\n<dd>I would be much more foolish than I have been. In fact,</dd>\n<dd>I would take very few things seriously.</dd>\n<dd>I would be much less sanitary.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>\n</blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Moments_(poem)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.internetaleph.com/detail/showdetail.asp?objtype=4&amp;objid=4&amp;langid=en&amp;pid=74\">Internetaleph</a>, Martin Hadis' site on The Life &amp; Works of Jorge Luis Borges. Retrieved January 10, 2011</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Excerpts from Herold's text are found in \n<cite class=\"citation journal\">Hinman, Strong (May 1935). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/23267240.1935.10620906\">\"Cogwheels\"</a>. <i>The Journal of Health and Physical Education</i>. Taylor &amp; Francis. <b>6</b> (5): 26\u201327. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1080/23267240.1935.10620906\">10.1080/23267240.1935.10620906</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Journal+of+Health+and+Physical+Education&amp;rft.atitle=Cogwheels&amp;rft.volume=6&amp;rft.issue=5&amp;rft.pages=26-27&amp;rft.date=1935-05&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F23267240.1935.10620906&amp;rft.aulast=Hinman&amp;rft.aufirst=Strong&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tandfonline.com%2Fdoi%2Fabs%2F10.1080%2F23267240.1935.10620906&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMoments+%28poem%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> Portions of this article, including attribution of the quoted passages, can be <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?ei=FJsYVKGYH-jhsATNlIAo&amp;id=_RdMAAAAYAAJ&amp;dq=%22i%27d+pick+more+daisies%22+%22college+humor%22&amp;q=%22daisies%22&amp;redir_esc=y\">read from Google Books</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-borges.pitt.edu-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-borges.pitt.edu_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-borges.pitt.edu_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.borges.pitt.edu/bsol/iainst.php\">University of Pittsburgh, Borges Center</a> <i>Jorge Luis Borges, autor del poema \"Instantes\"</i>, by Iv\u00e1n Almeida. Retrieved January 10, 2011</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.livinglifefully.com/flo/floidpickmoredaisies.htm\">I'd Pick More Daisies</a>, full text, Living Life Fully Retrieved January 10, 2011</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">A text with the title If I Had My Life to Live Over is attributed to \"Nadine Stair\" in a compilation of works under the same title by Sandra Martz, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-918949-25-7\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-918949-25-7\">978-0-918949-25-7</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.borges.pitt.edu/bsol/iainst.php\">\"Jorge Luis Borges, autor del poema \"Instantes<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Jorge+Luis+Borges%2C+autor+del+poema+%22Instantes%22&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.borges.pitt.edu%2Fbsol%2Fiainst.php&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMoments+%28poem%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-autogenerated1-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-autogenerated1_7-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-autogenerated1_7-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Almeida, op. cit.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/318997.html\">Env\u00eda Bono, de U2, mensaje de aliento durante Telet\u00f3n</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/El_Universal_(Mexico_City)\" title=\"El Universal (Mexico City)\">El Universal</a> online, December 3, 2005. Retrieved January 10, 2011. Bono was interviewed by telephone</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"Moments\", translated by Alastair Reid. Queen\u2019s Quarterly 99.3, Fall 1992. Cited by <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.borges.pitt.edu/bsol/iainst.php\">Iv\u00e1n Almeida</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2143\nCached time: 20180922005621\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.216 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.250 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 415/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 4153/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 446/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 15/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 6176/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.139/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 8.94 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  222.556      1 -total\n 66.40%  147.782      1 Template:Lang-es\n 14.31%   31.849      1 Template:Cite_journal\n 11.82%   26.310      1 Template:ISBN\n  5.04%   11.207      1 Template:Catalog_lookup_link\n  2.40%    5.344      1 Template:Error-small\n  2.28%    5.072      1 Template:Cite_web\n  1.96%    4.352      3 Template:Yesno-no\n  1.10%    2.437      3 Template:Yesno\n  0.96%    2.142      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:30404798-0!canonical and timestamp 2018092200562